<br>
Yes, I'm against it BUT, and here's the key thing.  I've never expressed that anyplace other than here and the only reason I did so is because it's the only medium we have to communicate.<br>
<br>
I would not vote gay marriages into law but if it became the law I would support it.  I do not do anything to treat any other person differently than I do anyone else unless I'm given a reason to, being gay is not a reason to treat a person differently IMHO.<br>
<br>
If they simply changed the wording from marriage to union or something along those lines.  I know it's a small thing and maybe even silly but to me a marriage is between a man and a woman, anything else just isn't right.<br>
<br>
That had nothing to do with my daughter though, I'm not at all sure where you got that from.  I've taught her that there are gay people in the world and that gets lumped right in there with the whole &quot;don't judge by color&quot; thing.<br>
<br>
She has an advantage my generation did not have, she watches &quot;Will &amp; Grace&quot; with her mom and that show has done much to &quot;normalize&quot; homosexuality as an everyday type of thing.  <br>
<br>
I personally think that's a good thing, I was very homophobic growing up (thanks alot Dad).  It wasn't until I moved to NY and had a gay couple in the apartment below me that I learned their being gay was not an infectious disease or that they were lying in wait to subvert me.<br>
<br>
*disclaimer I know Will &amp; Grace is not the definition of what it is to be gay, but I'm pretty sure that having a TV program that shows gays as everyday people living everyday lives helps to curb some of the misinformation that I grew up with<br>
<br>
