<br>
Just my two bits -<br>
<br>
1 - Excluding anyone from something based on race is racist. Period. Doesn't matter if the person/organization doing the excluding is black, white, yellow, or green. There are white racists, black racists, asian racists, martian racists. And until we stop labelling ourselves based on who our ancestors are and what colour our skin is, rather then who WE are, it's going to be that way. And I've been on both sides of it. Until I was in Jr. High I lived in a in a black neighborhood (and I'm white) and was called all sorts of names I do not care to repeat. Then moved to a dominantly white area and saw it happening to others. (And saying, btw, that they were just kids doesn't cut any ice with me. They learned to call people who don't look like them names from somewhere.)<br>
<br>
2- The site you linked is a book club, and a subsection of a company that has lots of specialized book clubs (see the trademark statement at the bottom of the page). Doubleday also has a mystery book club, a SF/FAN book club, a best sellers book club, a graphic artist book club, and probably many others I'm not a member of. No where does it say that only black people can sign up for this. Nor do I get the impression that only black authors are featured. This is their attempt to put together a package to help people of a certain interest group find material they might find interesting. The same setup they used for their other book clubs. Will they include in the mailings books directed at the white/asian/indian male or female? No. That's not their target audience with this club. Nor would they put &quot;Advanced Photoshop&quot; in the Mystery mailing.<br>
<br>
And yes, I know that had they made a club that was aimed at strictly the white point of view, they'd be bashed all to pieces as being &quot;racist&quot; and probably sued. And they certainly could have picked a better name for the club then &quot;Black Expressions&quot; although nothing leaps to mind.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying this club is or is not racist. That's up for the individual to decide. But in my opinion, there is a difference in &quot;special interest&quot; and &quot;racist.&quot; In special interest anyone SHARING THAT INTEREST is welcome. If something is racist, you are not allowed to join unless you are a specific race (or not a specific race, depending on the organization at hand). <br>
<br>
Again, just my two bits. Carry on... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mausoleumthenecro>Mausoleum the Necro</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Opinionated Asshole</span><br>  Posts: 932<br> <font color=#330000>(10/9/03 7:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1060.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mother fucking racist horsehit pisses me off</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You are stateing that it was the spam email that pissed you off. I want to know what the subject line of the email NOT THE FUCKING SITE, said, as that is what you are finding offensive.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
